WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:07.390
-It's good to be here.

00:00:07.390 --> 00:00:08.139
Thanks for coming.

00:00:08.139 --> 00:00:11.770
And I'm going to talk
about, I think, six things.

00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:17.570
First of all, I want to say
thank you to the institute.

00:00:17.570 --> 00:00:19.560
It is an amazing opportunity.

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:23.610
And I made some really great
friends and thought things

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.750
and heard things I never
would've thought or heard

00:00:25.750 --> 00:00:26.250
before.

00:00:26.250 --> 00:00:30.090
So it feels very lucky
to be here, very lucky.

00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:32.870
I kept wanting to make a
joke about-- something like,

00:00:32.870 --> 00:00:34.980
and I'm so glad now it's
a three year fellowship.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:42.260
And the second thing
I want to say-- We

00:00:42.260 --> 00:00:45.130
were listening to "Gratitude,"
Earth, Wind, &amp; Fire.

00:00:45.130 --> 00:00:46.760
Do you all know
Earth, Wind, &amp; Fire?

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:49.520
And you probably know Maurice
White died two weeks ago

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:50.861
or something.

00:00:50.861 --> 00:00:51.360
Maybe.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:53.760
Maybe you didn't.

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:59.070
But I've been thinking
about Maurice White.

00:00:59.070 --> 00:01:00.890
I was watching some
of Earth, Wind,

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:03.970
&amp; Fire's videos this morning.

00:01:03.970 --> 00:01:07.280
So one of the things
that I love-- I mean,

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:12.250
that was like one of the
groups that I grew up on.

00:01:12.250 --> 00:01:14.810
So you know, the music
that I grew up with

00:01:14.810 --> 00:01:19.330
and that my-- I kind of
grew up with my father.

00:01:19.330 --> 00:01:20.570
It was Earth, Wind, &amp; Fire.

00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:22.736
So I grew up actually right
outside of Philadelphia.

00:01:22.736 --> 00:01:24.650
And like, the other
little White kids

00:01:24.650 --> 00:01:27.450
were writing AC/DC and Def
Leppard on their books.

00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:29.100
And I was writing
Earth, Wind, &amp; Fire

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:30.860
and the Commodores on my books.

00:01:33.830 --> 00:01:36.640
I mean, if that song's called
gratitude-- My book's called

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:37.980
Catalog of Unabashed Gratitude.

00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:41.990
It just occurred
to me how formative

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:46.790
that that was and how beautiful
they were on stage-- I mean,

00:01:46.790 --> 00:01:49.430
the music is incredible--
but how beautiful they were.

00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:51.960
I was looking at them,
and Phillip Bailey, he

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:54.600
looks like he's the young guy
with the beautiful falsetto

00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:55.290
voice.

00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:59.420
And I remember-- They got
a song called "Reasons."

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:01.990
And it's like an adult,
grownup, sexy song.

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:04.300
And I remember being
seven or eight years old

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:07.814
singing the reasons
that we're here.

00:02:16.145 --> 00:02:19.320
[SINGING] In the morning,
when I rise, no longer feeling

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:20.860
hypnotized.

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:21.765
I was seven!

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:28.840
And then, another
thing I thought about

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:31.100
is that when I
was a kid, I would

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:34.530
listen to the music
with the headphones on.

00:02:34.530 --> 00:02:37.020
And I heard my dad one
time, who was a huge reader,

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:40.610
and I just wasn't
into books as you.

00:02:40.610 --> 00:02:41.110
-Heard

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:41.615
-Presently.

00:02:41.615 --> 00:02:42.490
Heard from my mother.

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:50.726
And I overheard my dad say, hey,
lea-- Cause I was sitting there

00:02:50.726 --> 00:02:52.850
reading the lyrics, because
I would get all records

00:02:52.850 --> 00:02:55.460
off the Columbia Record Club.

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:59.245
And I overheard my dad say
to my mom, well, at least

00:02:59.245 --> 00:03:02.330
he's reading something!

00:03:02.330 --> 00:03:07.000
So Maurice White and my big
brother taught me how to read.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.720
The second thing I wanted to
say-- So, he's in the room.

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:20.260
I have a teacher named
Lucille Bertuccio who

00:03:20.260 --> 00:03:25.540
is-- she might still be
alive, but she's on her way--

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:29.750
but she's a gardening
teacher in Bloomington.

00:03:29.750 --> 00:03:36.620
And you know, she's one of
our elders in Bloomington

00:03:36.620 --> 00:03:42.790
who has given so much
of her life to us.

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:46.390
I first met her because
I was at like an urban--

00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:49.390
like a foraging class, edible
weeds and stuff like that.

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:51.430
So you know, we'd be
eating like violets

00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:53.770
off the ground or
dandelions, which

00:03:53.770 --> 00:03:59.027
I love, and all kinds
of stuff like that.

00:03:59.027 --> 00:04:00.610
I took other classes
with her as well,

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:03.320
as she was an incredible
model of some generosity

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:04.849
and kindness.

00:04:04.849 --> 00:04:05.640
She's so beautiful.

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:08.359
I can remember her
walking down the street--

00:04:08.359 --> 00:04:10.275
because you didn't have
a car, so she'd always

00:04:10.275 --> 00:04:13.690
be walking with her cart when
she's going to the market

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:18.779
or whatever-- her laugh, her
incredible wisdom, her joy,

00:04:18.779 --> 00:04:21.920
her sort of rage--
you know, her sort

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:25.850
of beautiful, critical
rage at the ways

00:04:25.850 --> 00:04:29.050
that the planet's
getting fucked up.

00:04:29.050 --> 00:04:32.114
So anyway, I don't know if
she's still here on this planet,

00:04:32.114 --> 00:04:33.780
but I want to bring
her in the room too.

00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:38.990
And I'm going to
read a poem first,

00:04:38.990 --> 00:04:44.150
an elegy called "Burial."

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:48.910
So I ask this question
whenever I read this poem.

00:04:48.910 --> 00:04:54.150
Has anyone done anything
with their placenta?

00:04:54.150 --> 00:04:55.240
What?

00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:56.490
You.

00:04:56.490 --> 00:04:57.180
What did you do?

00:04:57.180 --> 00:04:58.800
-I ask people the same question.

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:01.000
-Oh, you do?

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.236
How come?

00:05:02.236 --> 00:05:04.470
-Because it's part
of the work I do.

00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:05.140
-OK.

00:05:05.140 --> 00:05:06.431
It's part of the work I do too.

00:05:09.330 --> 00:05:11.330
Did anyone do anything
neat with their placenta?

00:05:11.330 --> 00:05:12.930
Besides just-- I
don't know what you'd

00:05:12.930 --> 00:05:15.997
do with it if you don't
do something neat with it.

00:05:15.997 --> 00:05:17.330
Did anyone plant a tree with it?

00:05:20.960 --> 00:05:23.725
Thank you.

00:05:23.725 --> 00:05:24.600
It's called "Burial."

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:26.670
"You're right, you're
right, the fertilizer's

00:05:26.670 --> 00:05:29.120
good-- It wasn't a gang
the dullards came up

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:31.650
with chucking a fish
in the planting hole

00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:33.910
or some midwife got
lucky with the placenta--

00:05:33.910 --> 00:05:36.270
oh, I'll plant a tree here.

00:05:36.270 --> 00:05:39.900
And a sudden flush of quince
and jam enough for months.

00:05:39.900 --> 00:05:42.680
Yes, the magic dust
our bodies become

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:46.580
casts spells on the roots about
which someone else could tell

00:05:46.580 --> 00:05:48.010
you the chemical processes."

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:50.110
Probably someone in this room.

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:52.250
"But it's just
magic to me, which

00:05:52.250 --> 00:05:55.530
is why a couple springs ago
when first putting in my two

00:05:55.530 --> 00:05:59.550
bare root plum trees out back,
I took the jar which has become

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:02.310
my father's home,
and lonely for him

00:06:02.310 --> 00:06:06.200
and hoping to coax him back
for my mother as much as me,

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:08.600
poured some of them
in the planting holes.

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:11.770
And he dove in glad
for the robust air,

00:06:11.770 --> 00:06:15.710
saddling a slight gust
into to my nose and mouth,

00:06:15.710 --> 00:06:18.770
chucking as I coughed,
but mostly he disappeared

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:22.290
into the minor yawns in the
earth into which I placed

00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:25.090
the trees, splaying
wide their roots,

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:29.770
casting the grey dust of my old
man evenly throughout the hole,

00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:33.540
replacing then the clods
of dense Indiana soil until

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:37.660
the roots and my
father were buried,

00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:41.230
watering it all in with one
hand while holding the tree with

00:06:41.230 --> 00:06:45.100
the other straight as a flag
to the nation of simple joy

00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:48.750
of which my father is now
a naturalized citizen,

00:06:48.750 --> 00:06:51.880
waving the flag from
his subterranean layer,

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:55.120
the roots curled around him
like shawls or jungle gyms,

00:06:55.120 --> 00:06:57.720
like hookahs or the
arms of ancestors,

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:00.160
before breast-stroking
into the xylem--"

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:02.040
Lucille taught me that word--

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:04.470
"Riding the elevator
up through the cambium

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:08.230
and into the leaves where, when
you put your ear close enough,

00:07:08.230 --> 00:07:12.070
you can hear him whisper
good morning, where,

00:07:12.070 --> 00:07:14.200
if you close your eyes
and push your face

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:16.890
you can feel his
stubbly jowls and good

00:07:16.890 --> 00:07:20.720
lord this year he would giddy
at the first real fruit set

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:24.760
and nestled into the 30 or
40 plums in the two trees,

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:27.750
peering out from the sweet
meat with his hands pressed

00:07:27.750 --> 00:07:31.310
against the purple skin
like cathedral glass,

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:33.920
and imagine his joy
as the sun wizarded

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:35.730
forth those abundant sugars.

00:07:35.730 --> 00:07:39.400
And I plodded barefoot and
prayerful at the first right

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:43.070
plum's swell and blush,
almost weepy conjuring

00:07:43.070 --> 00:07:46.580
some surely ponderous averse to
convey this bottomless grace--

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:49.710
you know, oh father oh
father kind of stuff--

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:53.440
hundreds of hot air balloons
filling the sky in my chest,

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:57.710
replacing his intubated body
listing like a boat keel side

00:07:57.710 --> 00:08:01.010
up, replacing the
steady stream of water

00:08:01.010 --> 00:08:04.050
from the one eye which his
brother wiped before removing

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:07.070
the tube, keeping his
hand on the forehead

00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:10.440
until the last wind in
his body wandered off,

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:12.840
while my brother
wailed like an animal.

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:17.210
And my mother said,
weeping, it's OK.

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:21.640
It's OK, you can go, at all
of which my father guffawed

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:25.600
by kicking from the first bite
buckets of juice down my chin,

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:28.010
staining one of my two
button-down shirts,

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:32.450
the salmon colored silk one,
hollering there's more of that!

00:08:32.450 --> 00:08:36.590
almost dancing in the
plum, in the tree,

00:08:36.590 --> 00:08:40.780
the way he did as a person,
bent over and biting his lip

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:44.290
and chucking the one hip out
then the other with his elbows

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:48.250
cocked and fists loosely made
and eyes closed and mouth

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:50.130
made trumpet when
he knew he could

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:56.165
make you happy just by being
a little silly and sweet."

00:08:56.165 --> 00:08:57.596
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:57.596 --> 00:08:58.550
Thank you.

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:03.210
This is my talk.

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:08.300
I wrote it this weekend.

00:09:08.300 --> 00:09:10.830
And I thought I was going
to write a little thing

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:13.070
and then do some other thing.

00:09:13.070 --> 00:09:16.480
But then this thing
just keeps on coming.

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:18.910
I think it's called
"A Book of Flowers."

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:21.750
And I don't know if I will
call it "A Book of Flowers"

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:26.696
before the part that I'm going
to read to you or after that.

00:09:26.696 --> 00:09:28.820
But I just called it "A
Book of Flowers" before it,

00:09:28.820 --> 00:09:31.680
so we have to go from there.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:32.800
"A Book of Flowers."

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:35.380
I'll say it again, I don't care!

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:39.320
So the deal was-- This is from
an interview between my friend

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:41.140
Kyla who-- for the
record, I don't

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:44.650
know I got this right
yet-- She's also

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:47.780
part of this African American
poetry community, Cave Canem,

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:48.510
that I belong to.

00:09:53.730 --> 00:09:57.910
She is coaxing this out of me.

00:09:57.910 --> 00:10:01.200
She's like my teacher
in this, in a way.

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:03.269
She asks me in the
interview, "There's

00:10:03.269 --> 00:10:05.060
a lot of grief in
catalog, but there's also

00:10:05.060 --> 00:10:06.910
a tremendous amount of joy.

00:10:06.910 --> 00:10:08.510
By the time I got
to the poem weeping

00:10:08.510 --> 00:10:11.445
and about the niece who's made
a friend in this butterfly--"

00:10:11.445 --> 00:10:14.830
I had this poem about my
niece and she becomes friends

00:10:14.830 --> 00:10:16.890
with a butterfly--
"I was thinking,

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:21.230
I'm reading a book of poems
about flowers by a black man.

00:10:21.230 --> 00:10:23.990
Even though you do talk
about things related to race,

00:10:23.990 --> 00:10:26.460
I wondered if you were
resisting all the things you

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:27.910
could've been talking about.

00:10:27.910 --> 00:10:29.492
Was any of that conscious?

00:10:29.492 --> 00:10:31.200
Or you just minding
your business talking

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:33.530
about your regular life?"

00:10:33.530 --> 00:10:35.460
Here's my answer.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:38.640
"If there was any kind of overt
action the book is taking--

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:41.710
and I don't want it to be
a book against anything--

00:10:41.710 --> 00:10:44.240
it's a book imagining or
advocating for something.

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:46.270
It's really-- like
the title says--

00:10:46.270 --> 00:10:48.620
It's advocating for
something unabashed,

00:10:48.620 --> 00:10:51.240
something vulnerable,
and you know, full-on.

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:53.600
If it's conscious of
any sort of confinement,

00:10:53.600 --> 00:10:55.300
it's a confinement
that I often feel

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:57.790
when I want to express
a sort of wild love,

00:10:57.790 --> 00:11:00.960
when I want to be full-on
about what I adore.

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:02.910
And that's maybe what
the book is most.

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:04.600
It has that kind of heart in it.

00:11:04.600 --> 00:11:07.140
It wants to be nuts
in love with shit,

00:11:07.140 --> 00:11:09.260
which includes
being heartbroken,

00:11:09.260 --> 00:11:11.800
all torn up about
stuff, and open.

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:14.030
And that can feel
really terrifying,

00:11:14.030 --> 00:11:16.500
that kind of openness
or attempt at openness.

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:17.480
I'll speak for myself.

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:18.820
That feels scary.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:20.860
When you're like,
oh I love this!

00:11:20.860 --> 00:11:23.540
Because then if someone's
like, fuck your little thing,

00:11:23.540 --> 00:11:24.770
that sucks.

00:11:24.770 --> 00:11:27.120
That hurts.

00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:30.130
The posture of irony is
emotionally easy to take.

00:11:30.130 --> 00:11:32.700
It's very much a way of
not being vulnerable, not

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:34.140
being addressed."

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:36.840
"A Book of Flowers.

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:37.920
One.

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:42.290
Kyla, you and I both know
this is a bullshit answer.

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:44.960
You gently said as much to me
when we ran into each other

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:48.010
a few weeks after we did the
interview over the phone.

00:11:48.010 --> 00:11:51.140
I said, hey, I'm going to try
to write another essay to more

00:11:51.140 --> 00:11:52.640
properly answer your question.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:53.940
There's more to say.

00:11:53.940 --> 00:11:56.980
To which you said,
yeah, I kind of figured.

00:11:56.980 --> 00:11:59.590
When we talked on the phone,
I was wandering around Oakland

00:11:59.590 --> 00:12:02.290
after a long day at the Black
Farmers and Urban Gardeners

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:04.970
Conference, a little bit
lost and a lot hungry,

00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:07.420
looking for a place to eat
that might have something

00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:09.970
substantial and vegan both.

00:12:09.970 --> 00:12:12.050
Not always easy to come by.

00:12:12.050 --> 00:12:13.570
When I did finally
find a place, it

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:16.382
was not both, for the record.

00:12:16.382 --> 00:12:17.840
And when you asked
me the question,

00:12:17.840 --> 00:12:20.570
I couldn't quite formulate
what it is I wanted to say.

00:12:20.570 --> 00:12:22.950
That's because I didn't
quite know what I thought.

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:24.780
Or maybe more
accurately, I didn't

00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:26.320
know I knew what I thought.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:27.850
Though I did, of
course, I did, know

00:12:27.850 --> 00:12:30.150
what it means to be black
man writing a book of poems

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:32.322
about flowers, as you say.

00:12:32.322 --> 00:12:34.530
Though, Kyla, there are many
other things in my book,

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:37.500
thank you very much.

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:41.520
I do want to say and re-say to
anyone who will listen to me--

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:44.290
thank you for asking,
Kyla-- that I believe

00:12:44.290 --> 00:12:46.380
in gratitude, 'flowers."

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:49.730
There's a kind of discipline,
an energizing and catalyzing

00:12:49.730 --> 00:12:51.930
and potentially
collectivizing discipline.

00:12:51.930 --> 00:12:54.670
What I mean is that, when
I'm thinking of gratitude

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:57.880
or the gratitude I'm thinking
of is largely about the ways

00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:00.180
we make each other possible.

00:13:00.180 --> 00:13:02.600
And gratitude makes
me more interested

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:06.080
in making people
possible, myself included.

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:08.640
Barbara Ehrenreich wrote
a pretty compelling

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:11.190
I'm-sick-of-all-this-gratitude
piece in the New York Times.

00:13:11.190 --> 00:13:14.580
It kind of flayed the 'I'm
so grateful for my Lexus SUV'

00:13:14.580 --> 00:13:16.170
stuff floating around
that I associate

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:18.919
with Palm Springs or something,
even though I don't actually

00:13:18.919 --> 00:13:19.710
know where that is.

00:13:22.710 --> 00:13:25.860
I'm so grateful for my
beautifully manicured garden,

00:13:25.860 --> 00:13:26.660
et cetera.

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:31.250
And that's very far from what
I'm talking about, as you know.

00:13:31.250 --> 00:13:34.240
I mean, how lucky it is to have
one of those Valentine's Day

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:36.930
cards that plays a
recording and a song,

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:38.560
this one belting
out the Supremes,

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:41.760
'I Hear a Symphony,' and your
murdered pal's voice telling

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:45.530
you, Ross, I love you
like an old Motown record.

00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:47.970
How lucky to have been
alive to care for your dying

00:13:47.970 --> 00:13:49.760
father after years
of hardly been

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:52.420
able to talk to each other,
to open his water bottles

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:54.780
when he couldn't open
them for himself,

00:13:54.780 --> 00:13:58.440
to scramble him a couple eggs
and convince them to eat it.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:01.080
How lucky to take a phone call
during your graduate workshop

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:02.860
from an unfamiliar
number, which was

00:14:02.860 --> 00:14:04.860
your pal calling from
the psych ward the day

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:06.930
after his suicide attempt.

00:14:06.930 --> 00:14:09.630
How lucky to have done a
beautiful thing in your life,

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:11.630
to have loved something,
to have touched

00:14:11.630 --> 00:14:14.165
with your hands this
earth, to have been loved,

00:14:14.165 --> 00:14:17.050
to have escaped, none
of which-- and Lord,

00:14:17.050 --> 00:14:18.590
I hope it's in the
poems-- implies

00:14:18.590 --> 00:14:21.850
evasion of sorrow or pain,
none of which, lord knows,

00:14:21.850 --> 00:14:24.990
implies not looking
back, not reaching back.

00:14:24.990 --> 00:14:28.000
No, I mean across,
not reaching across.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.810
If there's anything interesting
to me about the palms,

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:34.020
it's that they are motivated
by precisely the desire

00:14:34.020 --> 00:14:37.690
to reach across, which is
exactly what metaphor means,

00:14:37.690 --> 00:14:38.250
after all.

00:14:38.250 --> 00:14:40.500
Have you seen the moving
trucks in Greece emblazoned

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:43.420
with the word metaphores.

00:14:43.420 --> 00:14:45.420
My palms would be stupid
little things to me,

00:14:45.420 --> 00:14:47.370
if they didn't reach your way.

00:14:47.370 --> 00:14:49.420
Who has the time?

00:14:49.420 --> 00:14:52.900
But you said flowers,
so let's talk flowers.

00:14:52.900 --> 00:14:56.160
For instance, the mighty
dandelion, which in my garden

00:14:56.160 --> 00:14:59.040
is common enough for my
buddy to have actually said,

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:03.440
whoa man, I've never seen so
many dandelions in my life,

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:05.740
and which is edible
top-to-bottom and paints

00:15:05.740 --> 00:15:08.630
the asses of honeybees
gold, to boot.

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:10.850
Who thinks of the
arugula blossom,

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:15.260
papery, peppery, with somehow
a kiss as sweet at the end?

00:15:15.260 --> 00:15:17.920
And two, the false
indigo blooms?

00:15:17.920 --> 00:15:20.269
Who knows the false indigo?

00:15:20.269 --> 00:15:21.630
-Uh, yeah.

00:15:21.630 --> 00:15:23.840
-Well, you'll
understand me then.

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:25.980
And two, the false
indigo blooms.

00:15:25.980 --> 00:15:27.200
I'm not kidding.

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:30.150
It's uncouth to say so, but
I feel sometimes somehow

00:15:30.150 --> 00:15:32.340
the need to repeat
myself on this one.

00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:35.440
It makes the rivers
in my body fill up--

00:15:35.440 --> 00:15:40.280
which yes, is a not-great
metaphor for a sexy feeling--

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:43.870
while watching the bumblebees
lumber up to them, nuzzling

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:46.920
the blue petals until they
part and then some growling

00:15:46.920 --> 00:15:50.240
and quaking, before
the bumblebee crawls

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:52.990
from the cave, all
drowsy and pollen-lit,

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:55.050
and does it again and again.

00:15:55.050 --> 00:15:56.490
Can you believe it?

00:15:56.490 --> 00:15:59.690
How lucky for the precise
folk of the pear tree

00:15:59.690 --> 00:16:02.170
blooms from beneath
the bloomers of which

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:04.730
tumbles an animal
scooting in currents

00:16:04.730 --> 00:16:06.250
through the late spring air.

00:16:06.250 --> 00:16:08.440
You should by now have
wrinkled your nose

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:11.620
and thought poorly of me
and waved your dusty copy

00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:14.920
of Sir Benedict Cumberbatch's
Craft of Good Writing, First

00:16:14.920 --> 00:16:17.580
Edition in my direction at
how mixed my metaphors have

00:16:17.580 --> 00:16:19.960
become in this place."

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:23.590
It's true, that's
not a real book.

00:16:23.590 --> 00:16:25.920
But man, that made me laugh
when I wrote First Edition.

00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:30.230
I thought, that's a good touch!

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:32.350
"I'm guessing if you came
to my garden with me,

00:16:32.350 --> 00:16:34.280
it might happen to you.

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:37.120
And what about the chokeberry?

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:40.770
Not the same or as good as, but
kind of like the chokecherry--

00:16:40.770 --> 00:16:42.496
bitter, makes your
tongue sticky--

00:16:42.496 --> 00:16:44.870
which I used to pick from the
back of my grandpa's pickup

00:16:44.870 --> 00:16:46.810
truck in Verndale, Minnesota.

00:16:46.810 --> 00:16:50.680
And serviceberry, AKA
juneberry, AKA saskatoon berry,

00:16:50.680 --> 00:16:53.100
whose many aliases
pale in comparison

00:16:53.100 --> 00:16:55.820
to the many registers of
deliciousness and health

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:58.200
benefits of the simple berry.

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:00.970
And two, how lucky
for the goumi--"

00:17:00.970 --> 00:17:02.568
Does anyone know
what a goumi is?

00:17:02.568 --> 00:17:05.200
Aw.

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:06.510
Come to my garden.

00:17:06.510 --> 00:17:09.410
"In fact, yes, let
me take this moment

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:13.890
to say no small praise upon
the goumi bushes in my garden.

00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:17.520
Let us first attend to the word
in the mouth, which is itself

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:20.589
a kind of miracle, forcing
you to become a baby again,

00:17:20.589 --> 00:17:23.726
glottal and cute--
guh; before coaxing

00:17:23.726 --> 00:17:28.400
you to say ooh, you crooner,
you; and then to say mm;

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:31.530
which you know, is the
sound of the things;

00:17:31.530 --> 00:17:33.760
and closing out with the ee.

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:35.410
That's a happy sound.

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:38.420
And then let us acknowledge
too the no fewer than 8

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:40.850
trillion glassy
freckles shimmering

00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:43.480
the goumi's red surface,
which when you account

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:46.060
for the 8 trillion
goumi on this one bush,

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:48.835
makes a galaxy of
glassy freckles."

00:17:48.835 --> 00:17:51.970
I was imagining the
mathematicians, like,

00:17:51.970 --> 00:17:53.245
walking out.

00:17:53.245 --> 00:17:54.680
You don't know
what a trillion is.

00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:00.620
Not to mention that
the goumi makes

00:18:00.620 --> 00:18:04.605
its own nitrogen, its own food,
and who does that these days?

00:18:04.605 --> 00:18:06.845
Not to mention, the
silvery leaves also

00:18:06.845 --> 00:18:09.580
speckled, flecked
to mirror the berry,

00:18:09.580 --> 00:18:11.610
or the flower
preceding the berry,

00:18:11.610 --> 00:18:14.370
which is not quite like
the bell of a trombone,

00:18:14.370 --> 00:18:17.390
but I will say like the bell
of a trombone today, because it

00:18:17.390 --> 00:18:19.800
is one of the many
things in my garden

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:24.300
turns my body into a horn,
pulling me into the orchestra.

00:18:24.300 --> 00:18:27.030
And from that not quite
trombone or the trillions

00:18:27.030 --> 00:18:29.720
of them shivering on
the bush is belted

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:32.740
a smell both sweet and
creamy that drops me

00:18:32.740 --> 00:18:35.560
some days to my very knees.

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:38.590
And I haven't mentioned
yet the way they taste,

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:41.350
the way they hang on the
bush, slowly wisening

00:18:41.350 --> 00:18:43.700
into an unspeakable
sweetness which

00:18:43.700 --> 00:18:47.110
will every day from
late June to mid-July

00:18:47.110 --> 00:18:49.510
make you forget whatever
the hell it is you

00:18:49.510 --> 00:18:53.366
came out here to do, unless
you came out here to eat goumi.

00:18:55.880 --> 00:18:58.410
Or this-- I have a
good friend named

00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:02.000
Ginger, a neighbor's
tortoiseshell cat,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.570
and she drops by daily.

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:05.510
And she likes to hop
onto my shoulders

00:19:05.510 --> 00:19:06.980
when I'm bent over
in the garden,

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:09.220
so as to differently
see her world.

00:19:09.220 --> 00:19:10.830
Usually she gets
up there and she

00:19:10.830 --> 00:19:14.040
likes to mosey out onto the
gangplank plank of my arms,

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:16.050
wrapping her front
legs around it,

00:19:16.050 --> 00:19:18.210
smooshing her face
into my bicep,

00:19:18.210 --> 00:19:20.730
and hurting me a little
bit with her claws.

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:23.690
Gingie has a weird
and imposing swagger,

00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:26.095
a slight leftward
cast to her trot,

00:19:26.095 --> 00:19:27.470
maybe because of
all the time she

00:19:27.470 --> 00:19:30.130
spends huffing in the
catmint in my garden,

00:19:30.130 --> 00:19:33.330
her little white
ponch swaying beneath.

00:19:33.330 --> 00:19:36.340
And when she turns the corner
to my alley come April or May,

00:19:36.340 --> 00:19:39.700
which in southern Indiana is the
season of fledglings and baby

00:19:39.700 --> 00:19:42.650
bunnies and such, her
parents will set off

00:19:42.650 --> 00:19:44.660
a cacophony of
chirps and whistles

00:19:44.660 --> 00:19:48.660
and screams, like something
out of a Western or something.

00:19:48.660 --> 00:19:50.230
I'm thinking now
of an Eddie Murphy

00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:52.930
skit in which his mother becomes
with her slipper like Clint

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:53.430
Eastwood.

00:19:56.750 --> 00:20:00.000
One of these days, I saw
through the front window Ginger

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.906
come trotting toward my
house across the street

00:20:02.906 --> 00:20:04.280
with a murderous
look at her eye.

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:05.640
And I thought, uh oh.

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:07.300
And when she got
close, I saw she

00:20:07.300 --> 00:20:09.900
had in her mouth, a
baby bunny kicking

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:13.280
its cute, little, cute,
long, cute bunny feet.

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:17.100
I was mostly naked and barefoot
when I ran outside and startled

00:20:17.100 --> 00:20:19.710
Ginger just by slamming open
the screen door yelling,

00:20:19.710 --> 00:20:23.020
let the bunny go!

00:20:23.020 --> 00:20:25.110
Ginger dropped the
cute little guy,

00:20:25.110 --> 00:20:28.550
and it scampered off a few feet
before being recovered again.

00:20:28.550 --> 00:20:31.330
Now I throw a rubber clog that
was laying in the bee balm

00:20:31.330 --> 00:20:33.650
and sage at Ginger, a
more aggressive version

00:20:33.650 --> 00:20:36.410
of distraction, just
clipping her ear.

00:20:36.410 --> 00:20:39.050
And the bunny this time
made a good getaway, maybe

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:42.210
had a full second or two,
while Ginger looked first

00:20:42.210 --> 00:20:46.070
at the clog and
then at me, really?

00:20:46.070 --> 00:20:49.890
Did you really just throw
your size 14 Croc at me?

00:20:49.890 --> 00:20:51.850
Then she added, looking
back over her shoulder

00:20:51.850 --> 00:20:54.015
as she began her
pursuit, don't you

00:20:54.015 --> 00:20:55.850
know how stupid you
look in those things?

00:20:59.840 --> 00:21:02.530
The bunny bolted down the
hill in front of my house,

00:21:02.530 --> 00:21:04.470
and Ginger bolted
after it, and I

00:21:04.470 --> 00:21:06.928
bolted after them both,
barefoot and in my underwear.

00:21:09.620 --> 00:21:12.470
The bunny made a hard right
and boogied up the sidewalk.

00:21:12.470 --> 00:21:14.270
And though the
bunny was quick, it

00:21:14.270 --> 00:21:17.780
was not Ginger, who closed on
it almost immediately until, I

00:21:17.780 --> 00:21:20.660
kid you not, not one
but two blue jays

00:21:20.660 --> 00:21:23.940
dive-bombed her, screaming
the whole way down,

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:25.890
which did in fact
distract Ginger

00:21:25.890 --> 00:21:27.870
enough that the
bunny scooted away,

00:21:27.870 --> 00:21:30.660
crossing the street in the
fastest hops of her new life

00:21:30.660 --> 00:21:33.060
before getting into a thicket.

00:21:33.060 --> 00:21:38.000
Gingie looked up into the sky
with her paw over her face--

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:41.460
the jays were convincing,
very nasty, if pretty little

00:21:41.460 --> 00:21:45.990
fuckers-- defending herself
against another attack.

00:21:45.990 --> 00:21:48.640
And after Gingie saw
the jays perched back up

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:51.500
in the crabapple tree,
their chests flared up

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:55.330
and their wings reshuffling
like switchblades clicking shut

00:21:55.330 --> 00:21:57.500
and sliding back
into pockets, she

00:21:57.500 --> 00:21:59.240
looked around for
the bunny, which

00:21:59.240 --> 00:22:02.250
was by now in the next county.

00:22:02.250 --> 00:22:06.670
Then Gingie, after sniffing and
then licking first one paw then

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:08.699
the other, the way
sometimes basketball players

00:22:08.699 --> 00:22:10.240
will look at their
hands when they've

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:14.645
missed a couple easy
shots in a row--"

00:22:14.645 --> 00:22:16.136
I like that metaphor a lot.

00:22:16.136 --> 00:22:22.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:22.130 --> 00:22:24.240
"turned around and me and
shrugged as if to say,

00:22:24.240 --> 00:22:26.230
did that really just happen?

00:22:26.230 --> 00:22:27.320
It did.

00:22:27.320 --> 00:22:29.500
I saw with my own
eyes in my own garden

00:22:29.500 --> 00:22:32.640
which I feel so compelled
to write, to spend time in,

00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:36.190
and to shout about its beauty,
its wonder, its care to anyone

00:22:36.190 --> 00:22:36.880
who will listen.

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:39.480
Or this, what the parsley
looks like and flower

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:41.700
in its second year,
its weird stock

00:22:41.700 --> 00:22:44.060
shot up nearly my
height and the blooms

00:22:44.060 --> 00:22:46.840
like doilies peppered
with luminous wasps.

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:49.660
Or the drift of mountain
mint, its plumes poking

00:22:49.660 --> 00:22:52.500
from the dusty leaves
on stocks about me-high,

00:22:52.500 --> 00:22:56.660
so thick with thirsty bugs,
an orgy of bees and wasps

00:22:56.660 --> 00:22:59.410
and flitterers innumerable,
that when you part them

00:22:59.410 --> 00:23:02.960
with your hands, pardon me,
you might say, coming through,

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:06.370
you might say, and then
lower your face to smell

00:23:06.370 --> 00:23:10.390
medicinal floral sharp-- The
humming there of the bees

00:23:10.390 --> 00:23:13.770
you have become is probably
not unlike the sound of blood

00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:15.590
moving through your body.

00:23:15.590 --> 00:23:19.170
Or the last dance of the peach
bloom, that wispy outfit it

00:23:19.170 --> 00:23:21.800
shimmies out of before
swelling into fruit.

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:26.480
Kyla, do you know that ants help
the peony bud unwrap by licking

00:23:26.480 --> 00:23:29.150
from the sticky bulb the
sweet nectar you can see

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:33.350
dotted in the flowers' surface
in little luminous gems?

00:23:33.350 --> 00:23:35.410
Ever find a big
burly mustard plant

00:23:35.410 --> 00:23:37.630
that had volunteered
itself in the pine bark

00:23:37.630 --> 00:23:40.090
murch of the foot
of a blueberry bush?

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:42.680
Ever cut down what you
thought the mulberry tree that

00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:44.230
planted itself in
the wrong place,

00:23:44.230 --> 00:23:46.950
only to realize when it
wouldn't die that it was

00:23:46.950 --> 00:23:51.020
a peach tree these days grown
to 18 feet tall and heavy

00:23:51.020 --> 00:23:54.860
with a good yellow clingstone
more immune to the rock

00:23:54.860 --> 00:23:56.430
than all the others?

00:23:56.430 --> 00:24:00.630
Ever seen the blueberry flowers,
like the teeniest white gowns

00:24:00.630 --> 00:24:03.310
after a rain, the
bead of water topped

00:24:03.310 --> 00:24:07.010
in the flowers' tiny eye, your
reflection quaking in there,

00:24:07.010 --> 00:24:10.910
more like you than any
image of you ever seen?

00:24:10.910 --> 00:24:15.090
Every slid 20 sweet potato
slips into a patch of yard

00:24:15.090 --> 00:24:17.260
without even turning
the soil, without even

00:24:17.260 --> 00:24:20.460
shearing the grass, and
watch those slips slither

00:24:20.460 --> 00:24:22.890
into a carpet of
heart-shaped greens,

00:24:22.890 --> 00:24:25.550
and after the first
frost and loosening

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:29.540
the soil with your pitchfork,
slid your hands into the ground

00:24:29.540 --> 00:24:33.030
to yank out the clusters
of sweet brown bodies,

00:24:33.030 --> 00:24:35.920
soil-covered and true?

00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:38.880
Look at me going
on like this, Kyla.

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:42.520
I'm resisting your question
about resistance, looks like.

00:24:42.520 --> 00:24:44.450
But I'm not really resisting.

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:46.900
Truth is, I'm
making an argument.

00:24:46.900 --> 00:24:49.320
I'm making an
argument with my body

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:54.400
and the ground about our
bodies and the ground.

00:24:54.400 --> 00:24:56.560
Two.

00:24:56.560 --> 00:25:00.680
When I told my buddy--
Let's start again.

00:25:03.872 --> 00:25:07.260
When I told my buddy
the poet and essayist,

00:25:07.260 --> 00:25:10.070
and beatmaker and
dancer Patrick Rosal

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:13.894
that I was trying to answer your
question in a less bullshit way

00:25:13.894 --> 00:25:15.310
and I thought there
might be a way

00:25:15.310 --> 00:25:17.870
to do it through the
garden, through the ground,

00:25:17.870 --> 00:25:20.960
he sent along a little entry
in an essay he's writing.

00:25:20.960 --> 00:25:23.300
His piece, a seedling still--"

00:25:23.300 --> 00:25:25.250
It's a pun.

